// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Trading domain — STATISTICAL ARBITRAGE & PAIRS TRADING. Two related assets
// can each wander like a random walk (individually non-stationary, I(1)) and
// yet share a SPREAD that is stationary and mean-reverting (I(0)): they are
// COINTEGRATED. Trade the spread, not the legs — market-neutral relative
// value. Beginner→advanced: the cointegration idea (Engle-Granger 1987) and
// the cointegrating hedge ratio β + ADF test on the residual, distinguished
// from mere correlation; the GATEV-GOETZMANN-ROUWENHORST (2006) distance
// method (normalise prices, pick by min sum-of-squared-distance, open at 2σ,
// close on convergence); the AVELLANEDA-LEE (2010) Ornstein-Uhlenbeck model
// of the residual dX=κ(θ−X)dt+σ dW with mean-reversion speed κ, HALF-LIFE
// ln2/κ, equilibrium std σ_eq=σ/√(2κ), the s-score (X−θ)/σ_eq and its
// AR(1) coefficient e^{−κ dt}; the trade (long at z≤−entry, short at
// z≥+entry, exit |z|≤exit) and why it is +EV ONLY under genuine mean
// reversion. RISKS: cointegration BREAKS (structural change — the leg you
// shorted keeps running); crowding & decay (Do & Faff 2010); financing /
// borrow / transaction costs eating thin spreads; stops vs. "it always comes
// back" (it does not). Carries the interactive PairsTradingSim (js/viz.js,
// verified by scripts/verify-pairs-sim.mjs). ESTABLISHED quant strategy,
// web-verified refs. Educational, not financial advice.
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

